doc.after: The nuthatches constitute a genus â Sitta â of small passerine birds belonging to the family Sittidae.[2] The genus may be further divided into seven subgenera,[fn. 1] of which S. przewalskii belongs to Leptositta, along with its nominate subspecies, Sitta leucopsis, and the white-breasted nuthatch (Sitta carolinensis).[3] Nuthatches are typified by short, compressed wings and short, square 12-feathered tails, compact bodies, longish pointed bills, strong toes with long claws, and behaviorally, by their unique head-first manner of descending tree trunks. Most nuthatches have gray or blue upperparts and a black eyestripe.[4][5] (One recognizable feature of Przevalski's nuthatch is that it lacks the eyestripe common to most nuthatch species.[6])
